Standard Description: Solve real world problems involving multiplication of fractions and mixed numbers, e.g., by using visual fraction models or equations to represent the problem.
Unit: Topic 8: Apply Understanding of Multiplication to Multiply Fractions

item description: Identify a product greater than one factor based on the size of the other factor, determine factors that will give a product that is equal to the other factor, and reason about the size of products based on the size of the factors.
Cluster: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to multiply and divide fractions.
Standard Description: Interpret multiplication as scaling (resizing)
Unit: Topic 8: Apply Understanding of Multiplication to Multiply Fractions

item description: Use the patterns in the number of zeros and the decimal point in decimal numbers to find products and quotients when multiplying and dividing by a power of 10.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Understand the place value system.
Standard Description: Explain patterns in the number of zeros of the product when multiplying a number by powers of 10, and explain patterns in the placement of the decimal point when a decimal is multiplied or divided by a power of 10. Use whole-number exponents to denote powers of 10.
Unit: Topic 6: Use Models and Strategies to Divide Decimals

item description: Solve a world problem involving multiplying a three-digit whole number by a three-digit whole number.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Perform operations with multi-digit whole numbers and with decimals to hundredths.
Standard Description: Fluently multiply multi-digit whole numbers using the standard algorithm.
Unit: Topic 3: Fluently Multiply Multi Digit Whole Numbers

item description: Determine the relationship of the value of a digit in one number compared to that digit in another number.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Understand the place value system.
Standard Description: Recognize that in a multi-digit number, a digit in one place represents 10 times as much as it represents in the place to its right and 1/10 of what it represents in the place to its left.
Unit: Topic 1: Understanding Place Value

item description: Complete a line plot using a given list of data and use information found in a given line plot to add fractions and mixed numbers with like denominators to solve a word problem.
Cluster: Represent and interpret data.
Standard Description: Make a line plot to display a data set of measurements in fractions of a unit (1/2 , 1/4 , 1/8). Use operations on fractions for this grade to solve problems involving information presented in line plots. For example, given different measurements of liquid in identical beakers, find the amount of liquid each beaker would contain if the total amount in all the beakers were redistributed equally.
Unit: Topic 10: Represent and Interpret Data

item description: Identify a word expression that is equivalent to a given numerical expression that includes parentheses.
Cluster: Write and interpret numerical expressions.
Standard Description: Write simple expressions that record calculations with numbers, and interpret numerical expressions without evaluating them.
Unit: Topic 13: Write and Interpret Numerical Expressions

item description: Determine the volume of a right rectangular prism given the base of the prism, which is packed with cubes.
Cluster: Geometric measurement: Understand concepts of volume and relate volume to multiplication and to addition.
Standard Description: Relate volume to the operations of multiplication and addition and solve real-world and mathematical problems involving volume.
Unit: Topic 11: Understand Volume Concepts

item description: Identify a line plot that displays a set of data measurements given in fractions with unlike denominators.
Cluster: Represent and interpret data.
Standard Description: Make a line plot to display a data set of measurements in fractions of a unit (1/2 , 1/4 , 1/8). Use operations on fractions for this grade to solve problems involving information presented in line plots. For example, given different measurements of liquid in identical beakers, find the amount of liquid each beaker would contain if the total amount in all the beakers were redistributed equally.
Unit: Topic 10: Represent and Interpret Data

item description: Determine the location of parentheses that will make an expression equivalent to a given value.
Cluster: Write and interpret numerical expressions.
Standard Description: Use parentheses, brackets, or braces in numerical expressions, and evaluate expressions with these symbols.
Unit: Topic 13: Write and Interpret Numerical Expressions

item description: Graph three points in the first quadrant of the coordinate plane.
Cluster: Graph points on the coordinate plane to solve real-world and mathematical problems.
Standard Description: Represent real world and mathematical problems by graphing points in the first quadrant of the coordinate plane, and interpret coordinate values of points in the context of the situation.
Unit: Topic 15: Algebra Analyze Patterns and Relationships

item description: Determine the relationship of the value of a digit in one decimal number compared to the value of that digit in other decimal numbers.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Understand the place value system.
Standard Description: Recognize that in a multi-digit number, a digit in one place represents 10 times as much as it represents in the place to its right and 1/10 of what it represents in the place to its left.
Unit: Topic 1: Understanding Place Value

item description: Solve a word problem involving division of two whole numbers leading to an answer that is a fraction less than one.
Cluster: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to multiply and divide fractions.
Standard Description: Interpret a fraction as division of the numerator by the denominator (a/b = a ÷ b). Solve word problems involving division of whole numbers leading to answers in the form of fractions or mixed numbers, e.g., by using visual fraction models or equations to represent the problem. For example, interpret 3/4 as the result of dividing 3 by 4, noting that 3/4 multiplied by 4 equals 3, and that when 3 wholes are shared equally among 4 people each person has a share of size 3/4. If 9 people want to share a 50-pound sack of rice equally by weight, how many pounds of rice should each person get? Between what two whole numbers does your answer lie?
Unit: Topic 9: Apply Understanding of Division to Divide Fractions

item description: Round a decimal number to the nearest whole number.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Understand the place value system.
Standard Description: Use place value understanding to round decimals to any place.
Unit: Topic 1: Understanding Place Value

item description: Use the volume formulas to find volumes of right rectangular prisms, determine the total volume of a figure composed of two right rectangular prisms, and find the length and width of a right rectangular prism given its total volume and height.
Cluster: Geometric measurement: Understand concepts of volume and relate volume to multiplication and to addition.
Standard Description: Relate volume to the operations of multiplication and addition and solve real-world and mathematical problems involving volume.
Unit: Topic 11: Understand Volume Concepts

item description: Compare the products of two fractions  to the size of one of the factors.
Cluster: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to multiply and divide fractions.
Standard Description: Interpret multiplication as scaling (resizing)
Unit: Topic 8: Apply Understanding of Multiplication to Multiply Fractions

item description: Solve a word problem by finding the quotient of a four-digit dividend and a two-digit divisor.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Perform operations with multi-digit whole numbers and with decimals to hundredths.
Standard Description: Find whole-number quotients of whole numbers with up to four-digit dividends and two-digit divisors, using strategies based on place value, the properties of operations, and/or the relationship between multiplication and division. Illustrate and explain the calculation by using equations, rectangular arrays, and/or area models.
Unit: Topic 5: Use Models and Strategies to Divide Whole Numbers

item description: Place parentheses within an expression so that the expression is equal to a given value.
Cluster: Write and interpret numerical expressions.
Standard Description: Use parentheses, brackets, or braces in numerical expressions, and evaluate expressions with these symbols.
Unit: Topic 13: Write and Interpret Numerical Expressions

item description: Solve a multi-step, real-world word problem by converting cups to a fraction of a gallon and display the answer using a slider on a vertical number line.
Cluster: Convert like measurement units within a given measurement system.
Standard Description: Convert among different-sized standard measurement units within a given measurement system (e.g., convert 5 cm to 0.05 m), and use these conversions in solving multi-step, real world problems.
Unit: Topic 12: Convert Measurements

item description: Identify rectangles and parallelograms and critique the reasoning of others about the attributes of rectangles and parallelograms.
Cluster: Classify two-dimensional figures into categories based on their properties.
Standard Description: Understand that attributes belonging to a category of two-dimensional figures also belong to all subcategories of that category. For example, all rectangles have four right angles and squares are rectangles, so all squares have four right angles.
Unit: Topic 16: Geometric Measurement: Classify Two Dimensional Figures

item description: Find the quotients of 4-digit dividends and 2-digit divisors.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Perform operations with multi-digit whole numbers and with decimals to hundredths.
Standard Description: Find whole-number quotients of whole numbers with up to four-digit dividends and two-digit divisors, using strategies based on place value, the properties of operations, and/or the relationship between multiplication and division. Illustrate and explain the calculation by using equations, rectangular arrays, and/or area models.
Unit: Topic 5: Use Models and Strategies to Divide Whole Numbers

item description: Estimate the sum of two fractions that are less than one to solve a word problem.
Cluster: Use equivalent fractions as a strategy to add and subtract fractions.
Standard Description: Solve word problems involving addition and subtraction of fractions referring to the same whole, including cases of unlike denominators, e.g., by using visual fraction models or equations to represent the problem. Use benchmark fractions and number sense of fractions to estimate mentally and assess the reasonableness of answers.
Unit: Topic 7: Use Equivelent Fractions and Strategies to Add and Subtract Fractions

item description: Identify the statement that describes finding the volume of a right rectangular prism using unit cubes.
Cluster: Geometric measurement: Understand concepts of volume and relate volume to multiplication and to addition.
Standard Description: Recognize volume as an attribute of solid figures and understand concepts of volume measurement.
Unit: Topic 11: Understand Volume Concepts

item description: Solve a real-world problem by multiplying two fractions with unlike denominators.
Cluster: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to multiply and divide fractions.
Standard Description: Solve real world problems involving multiplication of fractions and mixed numbers, e.g., by using visual fraction models or equations to represent the problem.
Unit: Topic 8: Apply Understanding of Multiplication to Multiply Fractions

item description: Determine the next three numbers in two different patterns given the rules of the patterns and the first two numbers in each pattern, and plot two ordered pairs created from corresponding terms on a coordinate plane.
Cluster: Analyze patterns and relationships.
Standard Description: Generate two numerical patterns using two given rules. Identify apparent relationships between corresponding terms. Form ordered pairs consisting of corresponding terms from the two patterns, and graph the ordered pairs on a coordinate plane. For example, given the rule Add 3 and the starting number 0, and given the rule Add 6 and the starting number 0, generate terms in the resulting sequences, and observe that the terms in one sequence are twice the corresponding terms in the other sequence. Explain informally why this is so.
Unit: Topic 15: Algebra Analyze Patterns and Relationships

item description: Determine the quotient of a whole number and a power of ten.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Understand the place value system.
Standard Description: Explain patterns in the number of zeros of the product when multiplying a number by powers of 10, and explain patterns in the placement of the decimal point when a decimal is multiplied or divided by a power of 10. Use whole-number exponents to denote powers of 10.
Unit: Topic 6: Use Models and Strategies to Divide Decimals

item description: Solve a word problem with fractions with unlike denominators and represent the solution using a fraction model.
Cluster: Use equivalent fractions as a strategy to add and subtract fractions.
Standard Description: Add and subtract fractions with unlike denominators (including mixed numbers) by replacing given fractions with equivalent fractions in such a way as to produce an equivalent sum or difference of fractions with like denominators. For example, 2/3 + 5/4 = 8/12 + 15/12 = 23/12. (In general, a/b + c/d = (ad + bc)/bd.)
Unit: Topic 7: Use Equivelent Fractions and Strategies to Add and Subtract Fractions

item description: Determine the expanded form of a given decimal number to thousandths.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Understand the place value system.
Standard Description: Read, write, and compare decimals to thousandths.
Unit: Topic 1: Understanding Place Value

item description: Determine the expression that can be used to find the volume of a right rectangular prism that is being packed with unit cubes.
Cluster: Geometric measurement: Understand concepts of volume and relate volume to multiplication and to addition.
Standard Description: Relate volume to the operations of multiplication and addition and solve real-world and mathematical problems involving volume.
Unit: Topic 11: Understand Volume Concepts

item description: Select decimal numbers that are larger than a given decimal number to thousandths.
Reporting Category: Number and Operations in Base Ten
Cluster: Understand the place value system.
Standard Description: Read, write, and compare decimals to thousandths.
Unit: Topic 1: Understanding Place Value

item description: Given the rules for two patterns, determine which numbers could be terms from the two patterns.
Cluster: Analyze patterns and relationships.
Standard Description: Generate two numerical patterns using two given rules. Identify apparent relationships between corresponding terms. Form ordered pairs consisting of corresponding terms from the two patterns, and graph the ordered pairs on a coordinate plane. For example, given the rule Add 3 and the starting number 0, and given the rule Add 6 and the starting number 0, generate terms in the resulting sequences, and observe that the terms in one sequence are twice the corresponding terms in the other sequence. Explain informally why this is so.
Unit: Topic 15: Algebra Analyze Patterns and Relationships

item description: Solve word problems involving division of whole numbers and unit fractions, identify equations that can be used with those numbers and fractions, and write a word problem that can be solved with a given expression.
Cluster: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to multiply and divide fractions.
Standard Description: Apply and extend previous understandings of division to divide unit fractions by whole numbers and whole numbers by unit fractions.

Cluster: Classify two-dimensional figures into categories based on their properties.
Standard Description: Classify two-dimensional figures in a hierarchy based on properties.

Standard Description: . Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication to multiply a fraction or whole number by a fraction.

item description: Solve real-world problems that involve finding the products of multi-digit whole numbers and justifying your answer to a real-world problem.

Standard Description: Fluently multiply multi-digit whole numbers using the standard algorithm.

item description: Identify expressions that are greater than a given expression by comparing the composition of the expressions rather than evaluating them.
Cluster: Write and interpret numerical expressions.

Unit: Topic 13: Write and Interpret Numerical Expressions

item description: Determine the location of points on a coordinate plane based on the value of their y-coordinate.
Cluster: Graph points on the coordinate plane to solve real-world and mathematical problems.
Standard Description: Use a pair of perpendicular number lines, called axes, to define a coordinate system, with the intersection of the lines (the origin) arranged to coincide with the zero on each line and a given point in the plane located by using an ordered pair of numbers, called its coordinates. Understand that the first number indicates how far to travel from the origin in the direction of one axis, and the second number indicates how far to travel in the direction of the second axis, with the convention that the names of the two axes and the coordinates correspond (e.g., x-axis and x-coordinate, y-axis and y-coordinate).
Unit: Topic 14: Graph Points on the Coordinate Plane

item description: Identify the relationship between the product of a fraction and a mixed number and one of its factors, and identify the rationale for that relationship.
Cluster: Apply and extend previous understandings of multiplication and division to multiply and divide fractions.
